To get a global view of a of daily rate, hourly rate, monthly income and monthly rate at once, a scatter plot matrix can be viewed. The red values are No on attrition and Blue are Yes. We can see that there is not much correlation between daily rate, hourly rate and monthly rate in terms of attrition. We can also see that there isnt much difference within the variables themselves as most of the box plots are of the same size. Lastly we dont see any correlation among each other. Since there is not much information about these predictors nor do they appear to add value they will be ommited from the analysis.

There appears that there inst much of a difference between Age, Percent Salary Hike, Years Since Last Promotion and Attrition variables. We can explore this more by doing a t test for these variables and if there is no difference between means we will remove these variables as they are not good predictors. After performing a Welchs t test we can reject the null hypothesis for Age only and fail to reject the null hypothesis for Percent Salary Hike and Years Since Last Promotion. There is significant evidence to suggest that there is a difference between age for Attrition Yes and No. Since we failed to reject the null hypothesis for Percent Salary Hike and Years Since Last Promotion this suggest that there is no difference in Attrition between these two variables so they will be removed from our analysis as predictors.

t.test(my_data2$Age~my_data2$Attrition)

heatmap.cor <- function(df){
  df %>%
    keep(is.numeric) %>%
    drop_na() %>%
    cor %>%
    corrplot( addCoef.col = 'white',
             number.digits = 2,
             number.cex = 0.5,
             method = 'square')
}
heatmap.cor(my_data3)

#Logistic Regression Model comparison 
attrition.LogReg <- trainControl(
 method = "repeatedcv",
 number = 5,
 repeats = 25,
 summaryFunction = twoClassSummary,
 classProbs = TRUE
)
#LogReg on Training Set
attrition.LogRegTrain <- train(
  Attrition ~ .,
  data = attrition.train,
 method = "LogitBoost",
   metric = "Spec",
  trControl = attrition.LogReg,
  preProcess = c("center","scale"),
 tuneLength = 6
)
